cs.AI, cs.LO, cs.CC, cs.DS, cs.PL 

This paper deals with knowledge representation and complexity analysis of a formalism called L_{CIRC}, which is an extension of propositional circumscription. It also discusses nested abnormality theories (NATs) as a tool for modular knowledge representation. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also involves logical analysis and complexity theory, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science). Additionally, the paper discusses the effect of nesting on complexity, which could make it relevant to cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Finally, the paper deals with propositional logic, which could make it relevant to cs.PL (Programming Languages).
